  "text": "JCE Cryptography Provider Architecture Audit findings:\n\n1. **Provider abstract class** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`): Defines `public abstract class Provider extends Properties`. This is the base class for all security providers. It contains the inner `Service` class which represents a particular algorithm/service offered by a provider. Providers register their services using this class.\n\n2. **Security class** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Security.java`): Defines `public final class Security`. This class centralizes all security properties and manages registered providers. It provides methods to install, remove, and query providers. Providers are registered statically via the `conf/security/java.security` configuration file or dynamically at runtime.\n\n3. **SunJCE provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`): Defines `public final class SunJCE extends Provider`. This is the main JCE provider bundled with OpenJDK. Its constructor registers all supported cryptographic algorithms (AES, DES, RSA ciphers, key generators, etc.) with the JCA framework. It also provides a static `getInstance()` factory method for internal use.\n\n4. **Cipher factory** (`src/java.base/share/classes/javax/crypto/Cipher.java`): Implements `Cipher.getInstance(String transformation)`, `Cipher.getInstance(String transformation, String provider)`, and `Cipher.getInstance(String transformation, Provider provider)`. These factory methods resolve the appropriate provider for the requested transformation by consulting the registered providers via the Security class.\n\n5. **java.security configuration** (`src/java.base/share/conf/security/java.security`): The primary security configuration file listing default providers using `security.provider.<n>=<provName | className>` properties. This file is parsed at JVM startup to register default providers in priority order. Failure to load this file causes an unspecified error during `java.security.Security` class initialization."
}

